<article about="/us/threat-insight/post/phorpiex-decade-spamming-shadows" class="node--type--blog-post node--view-mode--full node node-blog-full _legacy_content _blog-full">
  



  <div class="breadcrumbs _legacy_element _breadcrumbs"><div class="nav-crumbs"><div class="breadcrumb__item"><a href="/us/blog" class="breadcrum__item-link">Blog</a></div><div class="breadcrumb__item"><a href="/us/blog/threat-insight" class="breadcrum__item-link">Threat Insight</a></div><div class="breadcrumb__item">
            Phorpiex – A decade of spamming from the shadows          </div></div></div>

  <div class="blog-banner">
    <div class="blog-banner__image">      <picture>
                  <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1920_750/public/images/Blog/shadows.png.webp?itok=SLpcOHP1 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1440px)" type="image/webp" width="1920" height="750"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1024_400/public/images/Blog/shadows.png.webp?itok=mmlTj6-A 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1024px)" type="image/webp" width="1024" height="400"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_375/public/images/Blog/shadows.png.webp?itok=zCNdWnVv 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 768px)" type="image/webp" width="768" height="375"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1920_750/public/images/Blog/shadows.png.webp?itok=SLpcOHP1 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1440px)" type="image/webp" width="1920" height="750"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1024_400/public/images/Blog/shadows.png.webp?itok=mmlTj6-A 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1024px)" type="image/webp" width="1024" height="400"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_375/public/images/Blog/shadows.png.webp?itok=zCNdWnVv 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 768px)" type="image/webp" width="768" height="375"/>
                  <img loading="lazy" src="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_300/public/images/Blog/shadows.png.webp?itok=Q-luiWRG" width="768" height="300" typeof="foaf:Image" />

  </picture>


</div>
    <div class="blog-banner__gradient-overlay"></div>
    <div class="blog-banner__heading-wrap">
      
      


<h1 class="blog-banner__heading">
      <span>Phorpiex – A decade of spamming from the shadows </span>

  </h1>

    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="blog-content">
    <div class="blog-content__sharethis sharethis_toolbox sharethis_32x32_style">
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_label sharethis__label">Share with your network!</div>
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_buttons sharethis_buttons">
        <div class="sharethis-inline-share-buttons"></div>
        
<span class="addthis_button_subscribe at300b UNCONVERTED" title=Subscribe>
  <span class="at-icon-wrapper block-subscribe-button__trigger block-subscribe-button__addthis"></span>
</span>


      </div>
    </div>
        <div class="blog-content__metadata blog-content__metadata-author">
      <span class="blog-content__date">  <time datetime="2018-05-24T23:15:00Z">May 24, 2018</time>

</span>
        <span class="blog-content__author">
                Proofpoint Staff
  
        </span>
    </div>
    <div class="node-full__body blog-content__body">  <p aria-level="2" paraeid="{aebb1cb8-47ad-4298-96a3-333576453b12}{173}" paraid="966304473" role="heading"><strong>Overview</strong>&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{aebb1cb8-47ad-4298-96a3-333576453b12}{179}" paraid="799815507">Proofpoint researchers have recently begun tracking the&nbsp;Phorpiex/Trik&nbsp;botnet&nbsp;(SDBot&nbsp;fork,&nbsp;referred to as&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;throughout this post)&nbsp;as&nbsp;several&nbsp;sophisticated actors have been using it to distribute a range of malware. Despite the recent attention, though,&nbsp;Trik, not to be confused with&nbsp;the&nbsp;TrickBot&nbsp;banking&nbsp;Trojan, is&nbsp;a relatively old botnet. It is&nbsp;not especially sophisticated or complex but&nbsp;has been active for almost a decade, flying under the radar and attracting&nbsp;a solid customer base of threat actors.&nbsp;As we began tracking this botnet more closely, we discovered that&nbsp;a number of&nbsp;familiar actors were&nbsp;repeatedly&nbsp;leveraging&nbsp;Trik’s&nbsp;power and distribution capabilities&nbsp;for delivery of their malware.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{c9ee9c66-58c6-48c8-8297-50ba6fd39a80}{14}" paraid="1607687344">Analysis shows that&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;has been present for a decade and first began spreading via Windows Live Messenger and&nbsp;removable&nbsp;USB&nbsp;storage.&nbsp;It later began including Skype in its worming&nbsp;capabilities&nbsp;but&nbsp;this appears to have stopped a few years ago and&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;now&nbsp;propagates&nbsp;via removable media storage and email spam.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{c9ee9c66-58c6-48c8-8297-50ba6fd39a80}{54}" paraid="518200971">During the initial investigation of this botnet,&nbsp;we observed&nbsp;the bot version&nbsp;included&nbsp;in the&nbsp;PDB&nbsp;string&nbsp;associated with the malware.&nbsp;Pivoting on this&nbsp;data point, we identified&nbsp;several more versions, all spanning a timeframe of&nbsp;over&nbsp;five&nbsp;years.&nbsp;However, there is no real noticeable difference between&nbsp;bot&nbsp;versions;&nbsp;the&nbsp;version&nbsp;is&nbsp;more likely to&nbsp;increment when there is a change in infrastructure as opposed to a feature being added or a technique being modified within the bot itself.&nbsp;</p>

<p aria-level="2" paraeid="{c9ee9c66-58c6-48c8-8297-50ba6fd39a80}{132}" paraid="1092360329" role="heading"><strong>Meet the customers&nbsp;</strong></p>

<p paraeid="{c9ee9c66-58c6-48c8-8297-50ba6fd39a80}{138}" paraid="1784414648">Malware families&nbsp;associated with recent&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;activity&nbsp;include&nbsp;GandCrab,&nbsp;Pushdo&nbsp;(which in turn downloads&nbsp;Cutwail), Pony,&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;updates, and&nbsp;various coin&nbsp;miners.&nbsp;Some of these, like coin miners, are&nbsp;not distributed by&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;in spam but are, instead,&nbsp;sent to the hosts infected with&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;and executed,&nbsp;likely&nbsp;for&nbsp;improved&nbsp;monetization of the botnet&nbsp;for the operator.&nbsp;Taking a single day as an example,&nbsp;on&nbsp;May 9 we&nbsp;observed&nbsp;instructions to download and distribute&nbsp;GandCrab, Pony,&nbsp;Pushdo, and&nbsp;multiple coin miners&nbsp;being sent&nbsp;to the&nbsp;botnet.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p aria-level="2" paraeid="{0d107113-b31c-486f-900b-af88329925db}{3}" paraid="736211038" role="heading"><strong>The&nbsp;bot, infrastructure, and&nbsp;sinkholing&nbsp;</strong></p>

<p paraeid="{0d107113-b31c-486f-900b-af88329925db}{15}" paraid="1096184040">Most of the bot’s internals&nbsp;were&nbsp;already&nbsp;documented in a blog post from 2016&nbsp;[1];&nbsp;little&nbsp;has changed since that&nbsp;post&nbsp;with respect&nbsp;to&nbsp;how the bot operates.&nbsp;However,&nbsp;one important difference&nbsp;between the 2016&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;and the current&nbsp;version of&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;is that&nbsp;operators&nbsp;have backtracked in sophistication by&nbsp;removing the&nbsp;anti-VM&nbsp;code&nbsp;from&nbsp;most&nbsp;of&nbsp;the&nbsp;samples&nbsp;we detected. However, they&nbsp;retained&nbsp;some&nbsp;of these features in&nbsp;other samples, including a&nbsp;version that uses a .NET loader&nbsp;and&nbsp;performs&nbsp;very basic&nbsp;anti-analysis.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{0d107113-b31c-486f-900b-af88329925db}{113}" paraid="204986035">Proofpoint initially observed the&nbsp;aforementioned .NET&nbsp;loader variant several months prior to this investigation and discovered that it had been attempting to connect to an&nbsp;abuse.ch&nbsp;sinkhole after they had registered several of&nbsp;Trik's&nbsp;C&amp;C domains.&nbsp;We&nbsp;suspect&nbsp;that&nbsp;this version&nbsp;is still&nbsp;in circulation&nbsp;as a&nbsp;result of&nbsp;Trik’s&nbsp;worming capabilities.&nbsp;We observed additional&nbsp;sinkholing&nbsp;activity&nbsp;at the end of April&nbsp;2018&nbsp;and&nbsp;the beginning of&nbsp;May&nbsp;2018.&nbsp;Shortly thereafter,&nbsp;the&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;operators&nbsp;immediately stood&nbsp;up another&nbsp;four&nbsp;C&amp;Cs, some of which are being reused from prior months, dating as far back&nbsp;2016. Shortly thereafter, the operators resumed sending&nbsp;campaigns&nbsp;-- in this case distributing&nbsp;GandCrab.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{a16c6c33-6036-4d19-854c-954b3c8bf45f}{4}" paraid="1169484618">Trik&nbsp;nodes&nbsp;communicate with their&nbsp;C&amp;C&nbsp;servers&nbsp;using the IRC protocol and campaign payloads are sent&nbsp;to the bot&nbsp;in an encrypted state using a custom implementation of RC4.&nbsp;We&nbsp;have&nbsp;also&nbsp;observed several&nbsp;C&amp;C&nbsp;servers that are active and spamming daily, each with a maximum bot count of 1024.&nbsp;Any connections to the botnet servers when the servers are full will result in a TCP packet with&nbsp;the RST flag&nbsp;set and,&nbsp;sometimes, an error message stating that the server has reached its maximum count of 1024&nbsp;clients.&nbsp;We also noticed&nbsp;that,&nbsp;shortly after a spam campaign, the&nbsp;C&amp;Cs would close their C&amp;C port until the following day&nbsp;at&nbsp;which&nbsp;point&nbsp;it would re-open, ready for a new campaign.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{a16c6c33-6036-4d19-854c-954b3c8bf45f}{92}" paraid="449997415">We observed version v5.0 of the bot&nbsp;both&nbsp;during&nbsp;the&nbsp;GandCrab&nbsp;campaigns&nbsp;noted above&nbsp;and&nbsp;being&nbsp;sinkholed&nbsp;in April and&nbsp;May. The PDB string for this version of&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;is shown in Figure 1.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{a16c6c33-6036-4d19-854c-954b3c8bf45f}{132}" paraid="357082495"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{a16c6c33-6036-4d19-854c-954b3c8bf45f}{137}" paraid="374328747"><em>Figure 1:&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;v5.0&nbsp;PDB&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{a16c6c33-6036-4d19-854c-954b3c8bf45f}{155}" paraid="1082973618">However, v6.0&nbsp;had already appeared prior to this activity with no&nbsp;changes to the codebase&nbsp;or infrastructure.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{a16c6c33-6036-4d19-854c-954b3c8bf45f}{183}" paraid="1998703515"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{a16c6c33-6036-4d19-854c-954b3c8bf45f}{188}" paraid="813227468"><em>Figure 2:&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;v6.0&nbsp;doc&nbsp;PDB&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{a16c6c33-6036-4d19-854c-954b3c8bf45f}{208}" paraid="2076935760">The only noticeable difference between these PDBs is the inclusion of ‘doc’.&nbsp;We observed another&nbsp;similar v6.0&nbsp;PDB&nbsp;containing&nbsp;‘js’ which,&nbsp;when analyzed,&nbsp;was associated with&nbsp;spam campaigns&nbsp;sending&nbsp;.js&nbsp;attachments.&nbsp;While the PDB&nbsp;should&nbsp;not be relied&nbsp;upon exclusively, it may be an indication of&nbsp;which&nbsp;file&nbsp;types were&nbsp;distributed&nbsp;in any&nbsp;given campaign,&nbsp;especially considering that these bots last for a single campaign before they are recycled.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{adbcfd21-9300-4253-b6de-7bd40cb36bff}{53}" paraid="483617625"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{adbcfd21-9300-4253-b6de-7bd40cb36bff}{58}" paraid="411882695"><em>Figure 3:&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;v6.0&nbsp;js&nbsp;PDB&nbsp;</em></p>

<p aria-level="2" paraeid="{adbcfd21-9300-4253-b6de-7bd40cb36bff}{80}" paraid="1106072776" role="heading"><strong>Return of the .NET loader variant&nbsp;</strong></p>

<p paraeid="{adbcfd21-9300-4253-b6de-7bd40cb36bff}{84}" paraid="98494622">On&nbsp;May&nbsp;23,&nbsp;2018,&nbsp;we&nbsp;observed the return of a slightly different, older&nbsp;version of&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;(v2.5, see Figure 4).&nbsp;This version of&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;uses a .NET loader that has the main bot split into several encrypted pieces&nbsp;saved in the resources of the .NET loader.&nbsp;Once the main bot is pieced together and decrypted, the differences between the bots is&nbsp;fairly obvious.&nbsp;In particular,&nbsp;the&nbsp;PDB&nbsp;shows a much older version and has a different user compared to the v5.0 and v6.0 bots.&nbsp;Additionally, this version has never been observed outside of the .NET loader version.&nbsp;Based on samples analyzed over the past few years, if this bot has this&nbsp;PDB, it&nbsp;appears to be exclusively associated with&nbsp;the .NET loader,&nbsp;whereas v5.0 and v6.0 have never been&nbsp;paired&nbsp;with the .NET loader.&nbsp;This begins to raise questions in terms of attribution and,&nbsp;initially,&nbsp;it appeared as though&nbsp;there may be several operators running different versions of&nbsp;Trik.&nbsp;However, after several days of downtime, the return&nbsp;of the .NET loader version is&nbsp;now using the same C&amp;C server as version v6.0.&nbsp;While the&nbsp;.NET loader itself is not particularly new, this version&nbsp;of&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;being pointed at a live&nbsp;C&amp;C&nbsp;is new because,&nbsp;prior to this activity, we observed all .NET loaders&nbsp;communicating with&nbsp;sinkhole servers&nbsp;for several months.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{adbcfd21-9300-4253-b6de-7bd40cb36bff}{216}" paraid="575509100"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{adbcfd21-9300-4253-b6de-7bd40cb36bff}{221}" paraid="768816631"><em>Figure 4:&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;v2.5PDB&nbsp;from .NET loader variant&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{adbcfd21-9300-4253-b6de-7bd40cb36bff}{235}" paraid="1511085939">There are&nbsp;slight differences between versions&nbsp;in the behavior of&nbsp;the bot&nbsp;on the infected host.&nbsp;As noted, the first difference is that&nbsp;v2.5&nbsp;still carries basic anti-analysis techniques that were observed in&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;several years ago whereas v5.0 and v6.0 do not include&nbsp;anti-analysis&nbsp;features.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{12}" paraid="1542338870"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{17}" paraid="1758465312"><em>Figure 5: Execution flow of&nbsp;Trik’s&nbsp;anti-analysis&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{31}" paraid="278164492">Trik&nbsp;utilizes several methods to determine whether it is being executed within a lab, but&nbsp;these techniques&nbsp;are trivial to bypass.&nbsp;Version v2.5&nbsp;of&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;performs the following:&nbsp;</p>

<ul role="list">
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="1" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="4" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{48}" paraid="708093864">Snapshot current running process, query a hardcoded list of common analysis tools, and then try to match one of them to one of the current running process&nbsp;names.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="2" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="4" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{57}" paraid="1575118371">Query each entry in a hardcoded list of executable names for common file&nbsp;names&nbsp;when dealing with malware.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="3" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="4" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{66}" paraid="1884675540">Check the name of the current folder to determine whether the name implies that&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;is in an analysis environment.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="4" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="4" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{77}" paraid="78230238">Attempt to establish a handle to each of the tools to determine if they are running&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
</ul>

<ul role="list">
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="1" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="4" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{84}" paraid="1361998001">Utilize the&nbsp;FindWindow&nbsp;API call with its list of hardcoded process names in attempt to find any of the analysis tools listed.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="2" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="4" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{95}" paraid="909778423">Query a list of hardcoded users to determine if the current user matches any in the list.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="3" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="4" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{102}" paraid="2140197452">Query Kernel32.dll and attempt to resolve the address of ‘wine_get_unix_file_name’ to determine whether Wine is present.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="4" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="4" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{117}" paraid="159996952">Determine if it&nbsp;is being debugged with&nbsp;IsDebuggerPresent.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="5" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="4" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{130}" paraid="1338046580">Finally, as described in the 2016 blog post [1],&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;will query the properties of storage devices and attempt to match several strings to what it finds in the STORAGE_DESCRIPTOR_TABLE.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
</ul>

<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{145}" paraid="2072317710">Each of the described techniques have their search strings listed in&nbsp;Appendix 1.&nbsp;If any of these checks returns true,&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;will exit but only once each of the checks has been completed.&nbsp;If these checks all return false,&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;will continue with execution.&nbsp;The only exception to the above is the final check, which happens after&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;has created its mutex and generated its IRC NICK.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{183}" paraid="990398740"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{188}" paraid="463639406"><em>Figure 6:&nbsp;Showing the application exit if&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;determines it is being analyzed&nbsp;</em></p>

<p aria-level="2" paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{218}" paraid="941806001" role="heading"><strong>Email templates&nbsp;</strong></p>

<p paraeid="{924507cf-4bd8-4c5a-a4e7-eda572168e2a}{224}" paraid="87934728">Trik’s&nbsp;email templates&nbsp;are straightforward and&nbsp;are hardcoded into the bot; they&nbsp;have not changed for&nbsp;several&nbsp;years,&nbsp;with&nbsp;randomly chosen,&nbsp;hardcoded&nbsp;email subjects&nbsp;(Figure 7).&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{11}" paraid="772357586"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{16}" paraid="1378754684"><em>Figure 7:&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;email subjects&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{34}" paraid="1513210924">Additionally, the body of&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;spam emails&nbsp;has not changed in several years&nbsp;and has been observed in several campaigns including Andromeda spam campaigns in Q4 2017.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{58}" paraid="1111471350"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{63}" paraid="390071308"><em>Figure 8:&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;email body and signature&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{79}" paraid="102275503">The email closing, however, does change for&nbsp;each message sent by the bot.&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;generates 3 random letters, converts them to uppercase, and prepends them to the email signature (‘aCustomerSuppor’&nbsp;string&nbsp;in the above screenshot,&nbsp;“Customer&nbsp;Support\r\n\r\n”).&nbsp;This behavior is shown below.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{119}" paraid="2026669438"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{124}" paraid="443940069"><em>Figure 9: Function snippet showing&nbsp;3 character&nbsp;random generation for spam email signature&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{138}" paraid="1136937229">The resulting&nbsp;email&nbsp;template&nbsp;looks&nbsp;similar to&nbsp;those from a&nbsp;GandCrab&nbsp;campaign on&nbsp;April 23,&nbsp;2018, with the customer support line varying.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{172}" paraid="950298953"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{177}" paraid="1552184871"><em>Figure 10:&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;email from the April 23rd&nbsp;2018&nbsp;GandCrab&nbsp;campaign&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{199}" paraid="737268383">Sender names are&nbsp;randomly selected from&nbsp;two&nbsp;lists&nbsp;of first names and surnames, both hardcoded in every&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;binary&nbsp;we have&nbsp;observed so far,&nbsp;as opposed to&nbsp;other spam botnets that tend to send lists&nbsp;from the&nbsp;C&amp;C&nbsp;at the beginning of a campaign.&nbsp;The sender emails in these campaigns follow a very basic and obvious structure: &lt;hardcoded name in the EXE&gt;[0-9]{2}@[0-9]{4}.com&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{243}" paraid="785510433">Some of the sender addresses observed in the April 23&nbsp;GandCrab&nbsp;campaign include:&nbsp;</p>

<ul role="list">
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="1" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="1" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{79556bc0-3b97-40f5-ad50-5225e635af4e}{253}" paraid="1503322236">Humberto Anderson &lt;Humberto63@8117.com&gt;&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
</ul>

<ul role="list">
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="1" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="1" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{5}" paraid="631431448">Glenn Murphy &lt;Glenn99@3968.com&gt;&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="2" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="1" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{12}" paraid="1639216323">Bobbie Adams &lt;Bobbie57@9223.com&gt;&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
</ul>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{21}" paraid="731373810"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{24}" paraid="221883040"><em>Figure 11:&nbsp;Hardcoded names used for spam email sender names&nbsp;</em></p>

<p aria-level="2" paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{34}" paraid="513397069" role="heading"><strong>Traffic Analysis&nbsp;</strong></p>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{40}" paraid="254594183">Trik’s&nbsp;command and control uses the IRC protocol and, as previously documented, the&nbsp;C&amp;C&nbsp;traffic flow for these bots is&nbsp;as follows:&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<ul role="list">
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="1" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="3" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{64}" paraid="1882237472">Initially join&nbsp;a hardcoded IRC channel on the&nbsp;C&amp;C&nbsp;with&nbsp;nickname in format:&nbsp;a pipe enclosed ISO Alpha-3 country code followed by a randomly generated string of [a-z].&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
</ul>

<ul role="list">
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="1" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="3" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{85}" paraid="1775682893">If a bot exists with the same NICK, the botnet responds with the code ‘433’ which forces the bot to retry with a new,&nbsp;randomly generated NICK.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="2" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="3" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{100}" paraid="964515504">Once the bot has joined the server, it&nbsp;immediately receives&nbsp;a list of instructions which are typically&nbsp;used&nbsp;to join additional channels&nbsp;or close the connection.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="3" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="3" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{115}" paraid="515995199">Several different channels have been observed and they appear to rotate on a daily basis.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
	<li aria-setsize="-1" data-aria-level="1" data-aria-posinset="4" data-font="Symbol" data-leveltext="" data-listid="3" role="listitem">
	<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{126}" paraid="607604449">Upon joining these additional channels,&nbsp;the bot is&nbsp;provided several encrypted URLs that contain malicious payloads.&nbsp; These payloads are then downloaded by the bot and either executed on the host infected with&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;or sent in spam email campaigns, depending on&nbsp;the&nbsp;task specified by the botnet.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
</ul>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{137}" paraid="1836834776">Figure 12 shows a sample&nbsp;of the traffic from this botnet.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{151}" paraid="1145526715"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{156}" paraid="435342621"><em>Figure 12:&nbsp;Pcap&nbsp;snippet highlighting RC4 encrypted URLs&nbsp;(payload locations)&nbsp;sent to the bot for either execution on the system infected by the bot or to be distributed in email spam campaigns.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{176}" paraid="4858610">The encrypted URLs sent from the botnet are&nbsp;the&nbsp;snippets of decimals&nbsp;in the form of pipe-enclosed digits.&nbsp;These URLs are encrypted with a custom implementation of RC4 and can be decrypted with the following modified RC4 implementation in Python:&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{194}" paraid="1295480672"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{199}" paraid="925581410"><em>Figure 13: Pseudo-code of the custom RC4 implementation&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{211}" paraid="290568285"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{216}" paraid="868200011"><em>Figure 14:&nbsp;Python&nbsp;decryptor&nbsp;output&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{26b22b08-3208-4175-8770-e7d2fabdb9e7}{216}" paraid="868200011"><img alt="Custom RC4 decryption Python script" src="/sites/default/files/fig15.jpeg"></p>

<p paraeid="{91880c22-a12e-46d6-8c32-b04fd5ccf168}{245}" paraid="1634615008"><em>Figure 15:&nbsp;Custom RC4 decryption Python script&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{16775ea4-c540-4905-9abb-7c9ce45be1aa}{2}" paraid="1567554043">The tasks mentioned previously are referring to the commands that follow&nbsp;‘332’ and&nbsp;‘.d’.&nbsp;In this case,&nbsp;‘.d’ is the download command&nbsp;--&nbsp;one of many different commands supported by&nbsp;Trik’s&nbsp;bots&nbsp;--&nbsp;and when followed by ‘x’, the downloaded payload will execute on the host infected with&nbsp;Trik.&nbsp;When followed by ‘u’, the infected host will download the payload, execute that payload, and quit the current process.&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;uses this process to handle bot updates and prepare for the next campaign.&nbsp;We observed&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;bots&nbsp;downloading updates&nbsp;that&nbsp;contained hardcoded channels the bot would have to join to receive the new campaign&nbsp;payloads.&nbsp;Once the campaign ends, the bot listens for PINGs,&nbsp;as you would expect with the standard IRC protocol,&nbsp;until a new update is issued&nbsp;and&nbsp;the cycle repeats.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{16775ea4-c540-4905-9abb-7c9ce45be1aa}{86}" paraid="1960580503">In some cases,&nbsp;we observed&nbsp;several payloads after the initial connection but for the most part, only 2-3 payloads&nbsp;were&nbsp;downloaded per campaign.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{16775ea4-c540-4905-9abb-7c9ce45be1aa}{102}" paraid="1220551149"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{16775ea4-c540-4905-9abb-7c9ce45be1aa}{105}" paraid="1964109537"><em>Figure 16:&nbsp;Another traffic example&nbsp;highlighting 5 encrypted URLs&nbsp;that are hosting various different payloads&nbsp;</em></p>

<p lang="EN-US" paraeid="{8232432a-01f6-49fd-8273-851d45aa418d}{2}" paraid="1213883774" xml:lang="EN-US">Trik&nbsp;uses a layer of SOCKS proxies to hide the real C&amp;C servers. We observed other malware including&nbsp;Ursnif&nbsp;using the same proxies.&nbsp;</p>

<p aria-level="2" paraeid="{16775ea4-c540-4905-9abb-7c9ce45be1aa}{193}" paraid="232942521" role="heading"><strong>Conclusion&nbsp;</strong></p>

<p paraeid="{16775ea4-c540-4905-9abb-7c9ce45be1aa}{199}" paraid="1112235492">Despite being a decade old and using IRC&nbsp;as a command and control protocol,&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;remains&nbsp;an&nbsp;active and powerful botnet&nbsp;based on&nbsp;the types of malware that&nbsp;it&nbsp;is distributing.&nbsp;Many different malware families have been&nbsp;being distributed by&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;and this activity appears to be ramping up with multiple daily campaigns.&nbsp;We will continue to monitor&nbsp;Trik&nbsp;activity&nbsp;as actors increasingly rely on this infrastructure.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{16775ea4-c540-4905-9abb-7c9ce45be1aa}{199}" paraid="1112235492">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{16775ea4-c540-4905-9abb-7c9ce45be1aa}{253}" paraid="1613485545"><strong>References&nbsp;</strong></p>

<p paraeid="{ff98a30a-3120-424c-b517-430593010f47}{4}" paraid="1629555013">[1]&nbsp;https://www.johannesbader.ch/2016/02/phorpiex/&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{ff98a30a-3120-424c-b517-430593010f47}{14}" paraid="56796659">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{ff98a30a-3120-424c-b517-430593010f47}{38}" paraid="548336908">2017319 - ET CURRENT_EVENTS SUSPICIOUS IRC - NICK and 3 Letter Country Code&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{ff98a30a-3120-424c-b517-430593010f47}{44}" paraid="973720493">2801390 - ETPRO TROJAN Malware Worm.Win32.Phorpiex.A&nbsp;Activity&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{ff98a30a-3120-424c-b517-430593010f47}{66}" paraid="1915405449">2821422 - ETPRO TROJAN&nbsp;Win32.Phorpiex.A&nbsp;EXE Download&nbsp;</p>
